'''Eric Kotz''' is a South Australian [[fisherman]], [[Scuba diving|scuba diver]], [[Sailor|mariner]] and [[social historian]]. He is the author of three books: ''The Jawesome Coast'' (2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portlincolntimes.com.au/story/3778245/jawsome-to-launch/|title=‘Jawsome’ to launch|last=Media|first=Fairfax Regional|website=Port Lincoln Times|access-date=2016-04-12}}</ref> and ''The Butcher's Son from Tumby Bay'' (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portlincolntimes.com.au/story/2816684/butchers-son-to-release-book/|title=Butcher's son to release book|last=Harrison|first=Billie|website=Port Lincoln Times|access-date=2016-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/192557189?selectedversion=NBD54013439|title=The butcher's son from Tumby Bay / Eric Kotz. - Version details|website=Trove|access-date=2016-04-12}}</ref> and ''Sir Joseph Banks Group'' (2018).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.portlincolntimes.com.au/story/5690583/kotz-releases-fourth-book/|title=Kotz releases fourth book|last=Cootes|first=Isobel|date=2018-10-08|work=Port Lincoln Times|access-date=2018-10-19|language=en}}</ref> His most recent work is dedicated to the eponymous group of islands in Spencer Gulf, South Australia. He lives in [[Tumby Bay, South Australia|Tumby Bay]], South Australia and his publications focus on life in the [[Eyre Peninsula]] and [[Spencer Gulf]] regions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mlssa.org.au/2016/05/27/tumby-bay-author-eric-kotz/|title=Tumby Bay Author, Eric Kotz|date=2016-05-27|website=Marine Life Society of South Australia Inc.|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref> Eric Kotz is a [[Conchology|shell collector]] and a member of Bite Club, a support group for survivors of shark attacks and the friends and relatives of victims.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-03-11/jawsome-coast-australia-tracks-great-white-shark-history/7240032|title=SA diver looks at history of interaction between humans and great white sharks|date=2016-03-11|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-10-19|language=en-AU}}</ref> In 2017, Kotz claimed that 3 or 4 sharks had been shot in South Australia as a form of vigilante shark control.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.northernstar.com.au/news/shark-observer-warns-of-vigilantism/3261433/|title=Controversial shark author warns of vigilantism|last=samantha.poate|work=Northern Star|access-date=2018-10-19|language=en}}</ref>

