'''Linda Kaufman Kerber''' (born January 23, 1940 in [[Brooklyn, New York]])<ref>[http://www.historians.org/about-aha-and-membership/aha-history-and-archives/presidential-addresses/linda-k-kerber-biography www.historians.org]</ref> is an American [[feminist]] [[intellectual history|intellectual historian]] and educator who specializes in the history and development of the democratic mind in America, and the intellectual history of women in America.
==Education== The daughter of Harry Hagman and Dorothy Haber Kaufman, Kerber received a B.A. from [[Barnard College]] (1960), an M.A. from [[New York University]] (1961), and her Ph.D. from [[Columbia University]] (1968). She married her high school sweetheart Richard Kerber, a medical student.
==Career== Kerber has been at the [[University of Iowa]] since 1971, and is currently the [[May Brodbeck]] Professor in Liberal Arts & Sciences, and also lecturer in the College of Law. She served as the president of the [[American Studies Association]] in 1988, the [[Organization of American Historians]] in 1996–97, and the [[American Historical Association]] in 2006. She was the [[Harmsworth Professorship of American History|Harold Vyvyan Harmsworth Visiting Professor of American History]] at [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]] in 2006-2007, delivering the Harold Vyvyan Harmsworth Memorial Lecture at Oxford on November 16, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kerber |first=Linda K. |title=The Stateless as the Citizen's Other: A View from the United States |url=http://www.historians.org/info/AHA_History/kerber.cfm |publisher=American Historical Association |accessdate=17 July 2009}}</ref>
She has received fellowships from, among others, the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]] three times, the National Humanities Center, the John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Fellowship, and the [[Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study]]. She is an elected member of the [[American Philosophical Society]], a fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]<nowiki/>and a Fellow of the [[Rothermere American Institute]], [[University of Oxford]].<ref>[http://www.uiowa.edu/~history/People/kerber.htm Linda K. Kerber, Department of History, Iowa University] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005055038/http://www.uiowa.edu/~history/People/kerber.htm |date=2009-10-05 }}</ref> Kerber serves on the advisory board of the feminist academic journal ''[[Signs (journal)|Signs]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://signsjournal.org/about-signs/masthead/|title=Masthead|date=2012-08-22|work=Signs: Journal of Women in Culture and Society|access-date=2017-08-23|language=en-US}}</ref>
==Works== * ''Federalists in Dissent: Imagery and Ideology in Jeffersonian America'' (Cornell University Press, 1970) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Federalists_in_Dissent.html?id=op6GAAAAMAAJ read online] * ''Women's America: Refocusing the Past'' (with [[Jane Sherron De Hart]]) (Oxford University Press, 1995; 6th ed. 2004) [https://books.google.com/books?id=zZenZ85jlVEC read online] * ''U.S. History as Women's History: New Feminist Essays'' (University of Carolina Press, 1995) (with [[Alice Kessler-Harris]] and [[Kathryn Kish Sklar]]) [https://books.google.com/books/about/U_S_History_as_Women_s_History.html?id=RxnwJxtwZCUC read online] *''Toward an Intellectual History of Women: Essays by Linda K. Kerber'' (University of North Carolina Press, 1997) [https://books.google.com.mx/books/about/Toward_an_Intellectual_History_of_Women.html?id=Q9YXYVv5fH0C read online] * ''Women of the Republic: Intellect and Ideology in Revolutionary America'' (University of Carolina Press, 1997) [https://books.google.com/books/about/Women_of_the_Republic.html?id=54VATFoaZpoC read online] *''No Constitutional Right to be Ladies: Women and the Obligations of Citizenship'' (New York: Macmillan, 1998) [https://books.google.com/books/about/No_Constitutional_Right_to_Be_Ladies.html?id=YAIo1k6SSKcC read online] Received two prizes from the [[American Historical Association]]: the Littleton-Griswold Prize <ref>http://www.historians.org/prizes/awarded/LittletonGriswoldWinner.htm</ref> for the best book in U.S. legal history, and the [[Joan Kelly]] Memorial Prize <ref>http://www.historians.org/prizes/awarded/KellyWinner.htm</ref> for the best book in women's history.
